WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:04.885
Pulmonary air leak syndromes occur when
air escapes from the alveoli and travels into

2
00:00:04.885 --> 00:00:07.985
places it should never be, like the
pleural space,

3
00:00:08.524 --> 00:00:11.425
mediastinum, or even subcutaneous tissue.

4
00:00:12.284 --> 00:00:15.564
For respiratory therapists, this is all
about recognizing when pressure

5
00:00:15.564 --> 00:00:19.584
in the lungs becomes dangerous and knowing
how to respond quickly.

6
00:00:20.165 --> 00:00:22.424
Think of the core problem like this.

7
00:00:22.985 --> 00:00:25.745
Increased alveolar pressure leads to
alveolar rupture.

8
00:00:26.165 --> 00:00:30.004
Once that happens, air follows pressure
gradients and dissects into

9
00:00:30.004 --> 00:00:30.905
surrounding structures.

10
00:00:31.745 --> 00:00:35.384
This can result in conditions like
pneumothorax, pneumomediastinum,

11
00:00:35.744 --> 00:00:37.724
or subcutaneous emphysema.

12
00:00:38.525 --> 00:00:41.084
Clinically, patients may present with
sudden dyspnea,

13
00:00:41.685 --> 00:00:43.705
chest pain, decreased breath sounds, or

14
00:00:43.705 --> 00:00:45.104
visible swelling under the skin.

15
00:00:45.784 --> 00:00:48.764
On exam, you might hear diminished or
absent breath sounds

16
00:00:48.764 --> 00:00:51.025
on one side, and in severe cases,

17
00:00:51.025 --> 00:00:54.604
you may see signs of tension physiology,
like hypotension,

18
00:00:55.224 --> 00:00:57.884
tracheal deviation, or severe hypoxia.

19
00:00:58.104 --> 00:01:02.384
From a board prep standpoint, always
connect barotrauma risk with

20
00:01:02.384 --> 00:01:05.165
mechanical ventilation, especially with
high pressures,

21
00:01:05.824 --> 00:01:08.205
large tidal volumes, or poor lung
compliance.

22
00:01:08.625 --> 00:01:12.805
Also think about spontaneous air leaks in
patients with underlying lung disease,

23
00:01:13.525 --> 00:01:15.165
trauma, or even forceful coughing.

24
00:01:16.224 --> 00:01:17.845
Diagnostics are usually straightforward.

25
00:01:17.845 --> 00:01:21.165
A chest x-ray can confirm most air leak
syndromes,

26
00:01:21.605 --> 00:01:26.404
while ultrasound is increasingly used at
the bedside for rapid detection of pneumothorax.

27
00:01:27.144 --> 00:01:30.065
CT scans provide the most detailed view
when needed.

28
00:01:31.224 --> 00:01:32.565
Management depends on severity.

29
00:01:33.245 --> 00:01:38.345
Small air leaks may only require
observation and oxygen therapy to help reabsorb the

30
00:01:38.345 --> 00:01:38.345
air.

31
00:01:38.665 --> 00:01:44.464
But larger or symptomatic cases require
intervention like needle decompression or chest tube placement.

32
00:01:44.944 --> 00:01:48.944
If you suspect a tension pneumothorax,
this is an immediate

33
00:01:48.944 --> 00:01:49.464
emergency.

34
00:01:49.964 --> 00:01:50.964
Do not wait for imaging.

35
00:01:51.364 --> 00:01:53.805
As an RT, your role is critical.

36
00:01:54.305 --> 00:01:57.485
You are often the first to notice sudden
changes in ventilator pressures,

37
00:01:58.184 --> 00:01:59.845
oxygenation, or patient status.

38
00:02:00.444 --> 00:02:04.245
You must recognize early warning signs,
adjust ventilator settings to

39
00:02:04.245 --> 00:02:07.544
reduce further injury, and communicate
quickly with the care team.

40
00:02:07.904 --> 00:02:09.345
The key takeaway is simple.

41
00:02:10.124 --> 00:02:12.964
Pressure can save lives, but too much
pressure can destroy

42
00:02:12.964 --> 00:02:13.404
alveoli.

43
00:02:13.404 --> 00:02:17.485
Your job is to find that balance and act
fast when things go wrong.

